1. e4 c5 2. d4 cxd4 3. c3 dxc3 4. Nxc3 Nc6 5. Nf3 e5? 6. Bc4 Nf6 7. O-O? (7. Ng5 d5 8. exd5 Nd4 9. d6 Be6) 7... Be7 8. Qe2 O-O 9. h3 d6 10. Be3 a6 11. Rac1 b5 12. Bd3 Bb7 13. Rfd1 Nh5 14. Nd5 Nd4 15. Nxd4 exd4 16. Bxd4 Bxd5 17. Qxh5 Bxa2 18. Bxg7!! { Computer eventually likes this move, but especially versus a human,
black must find only moves for the next 10 moves to draw. } 18... Kxg7 19. e5 Rh8?! (19... h6 20. Qg4+ Bg5 21. h4 Bb3 22. Bc2 Bxc2 23. Rxc2 Rc8 24. Rxd6 Rxc2 25. Rxd8 Rxd8 26. hxg5 Rdd2 27. gxh6+ Kxh6) 20. Be4! { No intention to take the
a8 rook, just getting out of the way for a rook lift. } 20... d5 21. Rc3 dxe4 { Black has enough material compensation for the queen, and there is no direct
mate on the black king, but the a2 bishop will be lost in nearly all
variations. } 22. Rg3+ Kf8 23. Rxd8+ Rxd8 24. b3! Rd3 25. e6 fxe6 26. Qh6+ Ke8 27. Rxd3 exd3 28. Qxe6 d2 29. Qc6+ Kf7 30. Qd5+ Kf8 31. Qxd2 Bxb3 32. Qb2 { The
availability of Qb2 is the only real reason that this entire Bxg7 line is
winning for white. } 32... Rg8 33. Qxb3 b4 34. Qf3+ Kg7 35. Qb7 Kf7 36. Qxa6 Rg6 37. Qc4+ Kf8 38. f4 Rg3 39. Qc8+ Kg7 40. f5 b3 41. Kf2 Rd3 42. g4 Rd2+ 43. Ke1 b2 44. Qb7 Rc2? (44... Rh2 { A heroic try for a draw. } 45. Qxe7+ Kg8 { How does
white win? Neither the pawn nor the rook can be taken, so even if white gets a
fork, he cannot capture. White must find the clever plan: } 46. Qd8+ Kg7 47. Qc7+ Kg8 48. Qc8+ Kg7 49. Qb7+ Kg8 50. Kd1!! { White will give the queen for the pawn
and rook, then win the rook-and-pawn endgame. An ironic ending to a game where
white sacrifices a pawn early. }) 45. Qxe7+ Kg8 46. Qe8+ Kg7 47. f6+! Kxf6 48. g5+?? { Horrific move that blunders a draw. } (48. Qf8+! { No matter where the king
goes, Qf5+ will win the rook. }) 48... Kxg5 (48... Kg7 { There are no checks to
win the rook and stop the pawn from queening }) 49. Qe5+ Kh6 50. Qf6+ Kh5 51. Qf5+ *


